explanation:
- OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET (macro): The call OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET(OS_impl_module_table, *token) is the key expression that might perform assignments or other side-effects. Because it is a macro, its expansion must be inspected to see whether it assigns to its 2nd parameter (which will be expanded to ‘*token’), or otherwise modifies the token identifier textually. This determines whether the pointer variable or the pointed-to object is modified.
- OS_object_token_t (typedef): Knowing the exact typedef (and qualifiers) is required to determine what ‘*token’ denotes (e.g., an integer id, a struct, or even a pointer type) and whether the const qualifier in the parameter declaration actually prevents modification of the pointed-to object. If OS_object_token_t is itself a pointer type, behavior differs.
- OS_impl_module_table (object/table): The macro uses this table symbol; its type and any macros/inline helpers associated with table access (indexing, assignment) can show how the second macro argument is used (read-only, written, passed to functions), which affects whether the token or *token is modified.
- OS_ObjectIndexFromToken (function): The static call graph indicates this function may be invoked (via the macro). Its prototype/implementation must be checked to see how it accepts the token (by value or by pointer) and whether it modifies the token or the object referred to. This reveals any indirect modification of the parameter.

Inspecting these symbols (macro expansion, typedef, table definition, and the referenced function) is sufficient to determine whether the token parameter or the token pointer itself can be modified, and thus whether the MISRA rule is violated.
